07676nam a22011055i 9783110753059DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107530597 a10.1515/97831107530592doi  a(DE-B1597)584735  a(OCoLC)1394871969  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090602bisacsh0485pa415qDE-101  aET 100qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27946:00aContext, Intent and Variation in Grammaticalization /ced. by Hendrik De Smet, Peter Petré, Benedikt Szmrecsanyi. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (V, 307 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v36500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 General introduction -- t2 Looking at grammaticalization from the perspective of short-time changes in real time -- t3 A quantum of salience -- t4 Maximizing the data-drivenness of grammaticalization research -- t5 From chance to epistemic possibility -- t6 The structured nature of prepositional meaning -- t7 Competition in antagonistic verb complementation -- t8 Promoting and inhibiting forces at work -- t9 Making interpretation redundant -- t10 Straddling a syntactic divide -- t11 The development of prose style in English horse manuals -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow is grammaticalization theory to accommodate the external factors that drive change and the competition that inevitably comes with change? This volume collects a wide range of papers at this intersection between grammaticalization theory and variationist linguistics. Grammaticalization and grammatical innovation, even if inevitably subject to formal change, are primarily driven by functional and communicative pressures. These include extravagant abuse of a construction for effect, but just as well reduction of its semantics to enhance its scope. Variation is shown to feed into this process through various means, including social embedding, functional competition (between variant constructions or between functions within a construction), stylistic specialization, contact-induced grammaticalization, but also analogical support of variant syntactic patterns. Attention is also paid to the methodological integration of variationist thinking and grammaticalization theory, including the issue of relative weight of language-internal and language-external variables, and how to measure their interaction. This study of grammaticalization through the lens of variation is of interest to all linguists studying language variation and change.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGrammatikalisierung. 4aHistorische Linguistk. 4aVariationslinguistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Syntax.2bisacsh  aChange and Variation in the (English) Verb Phrase.  aGrammaticalization.  aHistorical Linguistics.  aVariationist Linguistics.1 aAijmer, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Smet, Hendrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Smet, Hendrik, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFonteyn, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeeraerts, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartmann, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHundt, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLos, Bettelou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLubbers, Thijs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez-Couso, María José, 